Born on December 14, 1877, in Liège, Belgium, she was known to have poisoned at least 11 people between 1933 and 1936, although she was suspected of more deaths.

Becker was a middle-aged woman when she began her criminal activities, running a small shop in Liège. She was well-regarded in her community, which made her crimes even more shocking when they were uncovered. Her method involved befriending elderly individuals who were often widowed, and then offering them financial advice or assistance. She would then persuade them to grant her control over their assets, after which she would poison them with digitalis, a substance derived from the foxglove plant that affects the heart.

Her crimes were eventually discovered, leading to her arrest in 1936. During her trial, the extent of her crimes came to light, revealing a calculated and cold-blooded approach to murder. Becker was found guilty of multiple counts of murder and was sentenced to death. However, her sentence was later commuted to life imprisonment. Marie Alexandrine Becker died in prison on July 6, 1942.

Born in a small village in the Andes, her case attracted attention from the medical community and the wider world due to the extreme rarity and young age at which she became pregnant.

Lina was brought to a hospital by her parents at the age of five, initially under the assumption that she had a tumor, because her abdomen was increasing in size. An investigation was conducted to determine who the father of the child was, but no conclusive evidence was found, and the case was eventually dropped due to the Peruvian government's intervention. Born Bella Akhatovna Akhmadulina in Moscow, she grew up in a family with Tatar, Italian, and Russian heritage, a background that contributed to her rich cultural and linguistic identity.

Akhmadulina came to prominence during the Khrushchev Thaw, a period of political and cultural liberalization in the Soviet Union. She was part of the first wave of Soviet poets who gained recognition after the death of Stalin, alongside other notable figures such as Yevgeny Yevtushenko, Andrei Voznesensky, and Robert Rozhdestvensky. Her work, characterized by its artistic innovation, elegance, and depth, often explored themes of love, nature, and the human condition, imbued with a personal, emotional authenticity.

Notably, she has served as the Minister of Women and Child Development, where she has worked on initiatives aimed at improving the welfare of women and children in India.

column1: Tell me a bio of Lees Knowles,Lees Knowles (1857–1928) was a British barrister, soldier, and politician, as well as a notable figure in the fields of military history and theory. Born on February 7, 1857, he pursued an education in law and was called to the Bar at the Inner Temple in 1885, though his professional life would span beyond the legal field into military service and academia.

Knowles served as a Lieutenant Colonel in the Volunteer Force, a precursor to the Territorial Army, showing his keen interest in military matters. His involvement in military service was paralleled by his academic pursuits in military history and strategy, contributing to his reputation as an expert in these areas.

In politics, Lees Knowles was a member of the Conservative Party and was elected as the Member of Parliament (MP) for Salford West, serving from 1900 to 1906. His tenure in politics allowed him to merge his interests, particularly advocating for military and defense issues within the parliamentary framework.

column1: Tell me a bio of Scientist (musician),Scientist, born Hopeton Brown in 1960 in Kingston, Jamaica, is a pioneering figure in the world of reggae dub music. Growing up in the vibrant and musically rich environment of Kingston, Scientist was exposed to the sounds and culture of reggae from an early age. His interest in music, particularly in the technical aspects of sound engineering, led him to apprentice under King Tubby, one of the founding fathers of dub music, at his studio.

Dub music, characterized by its focus on remixing existing recordings to emphasize the rhythm section and adding various audio effects, became the perfect medium for Scientist's creativity and technical prowess. He earned his nickname ""Scientist"" due to his meticulous approach to sound mixing and his innovative techniques, which seemed almost magical at the time.

Throughout the 1970s and 1980s, Scientist became known for his unique style, which included the extensive use of reverb and echo effects, transforming the reggae soundscape. He worked with various prominent reggae artists and producers, contributing to numerous albums that have since become classics in the genre.

column1: Tell me a bio of Terence Blacker,Terence Blacker is an English author, columnist, journalist, and publisher, known for his contributions to children's literature as well as his work in journalism. Born on February 5, 1948, in Hadleigh, Suffolk, Blacker grew up in a family with a strong interest in horse racing; his father, Major Anthony Blacker, was a racing manager to Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother. This connection to the racing world influenced some of Blacker's later writing.

Blacker was educated at Hawtreys, a preparatory school, and then at Wellington College, a public school in Berkshire. He went on to study at the University of Cambridge. His early career was not in writing but in publishing; after university, he worked in publishing, including a stint as a literary agent, before dedicating himself to writing full-time.

As an author, Terence Blacker has written both for adults and children, but he is perhaps best known for his children's books. His works often explore themes of identity, friendship, and societal expectations, weaving humor and warmth into the narratives. One of his most notable children's books is ""Ms. Wiz,"" a series about a quirky and magical teacher that has captivated young readers across many countries.

column1: Tell me a bio of Milton Diamond,As of my last update in 2023, Milton Diamond is a prominent American sexologist known for his research in human sexuality, including transgender, non-binary, and intersex conditions. Born on October 6, 1934, Diamond has made significant contributions to the understanding of sexual development, identity, and orientation.

One of Diamond's most notable contributions is challenging John Money's theory of gender neutrality and the idea that gender identity is solely a result of socialization. This debate gained public attention through the case of David Reimer, also known as the John/Joan case. Diamond argued that innate factors play a crucial role in gender identity, a viewpoint that was vindicated through his follow-up with Reimer, who had been raised as a girl after a botched circumcision but later reverted to his male identity.

Diamond has held various academic positions, including serving as a professor at the University of Hawaii at Manoa, where he has been involved in the Department of Anatomy and Reproductive Biology. His research and publications have covered a wide range of topics, including the effects of prenatal exposure to hormones on sexual development and orientation, the biology behind sexual orientation, and issues surrounding intersexuality and gender identity.
His work has not only advanced scientific understanding but also influenced medical policies","

column1: Tell me a bio of Kim Casali,Kim Casali (née Grove) was a New Zealand cartoonist born on September 9, 1941, in Auckland. She is best known for creating the iconic ""Love Is..."" comic strip, a series of love-themed cartoons featuring a naked boy and girl and presenting various definitions of love through simple, heartfelt expressions and situations. The series became widely recognized and adored for its charming and relatable depiction of love and relationships.

Kim started drawing the cartoons in the late 1960s for her future husband, Roberto Casali, as a way to express her feelings for him. The couple married in 1970. Her private tokens of affection soon gained a wider audience when they were published in a book and then as a syndicated newspaper comic strip in 1970. The ""Love Is..."" series quickly gained popularity around the world, being translated into multiple languages and appearing in newspapers across the globe.

Beyond the newspaper strips, the ""Love Is..."" characters were also featured on a wide range of merchandise, including greeting cards, calendars, and various gift items, becoming a significant part of popular culture during the 1970s and 1980s.

She worked primarily in the state of Veracruz, a region heavily impacted by drug cartel violence and political corruption. Martínez was a correspondent for the national magazine ""Proceso,"" one of Mexico's most respected investigative journalism publications.

Throughout her career, Martínez built a reputation for her fearless approach to journalism, often exposing the links between local politicians and drug trafficking organizations. Her work was crucial in drawing national and international attention to the issues plaguing Veracruz and the dangers faced by journalists in Mexico, one of the world's most perilous countries for the press.

Martínez's dedication to uncovering the truth came at a high cost. On April 28, 2012, she was found murdered in her home in Xalapa, the capital of Veracruz. Her death was initially claimed to be a robbery gone wrong by local authorities, but inconsistencies and the failure to adequately investigate her murder led many to believe that she was killed because of her work. Her murder sparked outrage and condemnation from international organizations and journalists around the world, highlighting the risks faced","

Tell me a bio of Anna May Wong,Anna May Wong, born Wong Liu Tsong on January 3, 1905, in Los Angeles, California, was a pioneering Chinese American actress who achieved international fame in the silent film era and beyond. As the daughter of second-generation Chinese Americans, Wong grew up in a laundry near Chinatown, where she developed an early fascination with the movies and dreamed of becoming an actress.

Despite the rampant racial discrimination and stereotyping in Hollywood at the time, Wong broke barriers to become the first Chinese American movie star. Her career began in the silent film era with her debut in ""The Red Lantern"" (1919). However, her breakout role came in ""The Toll of the Sea"" (1922), where she played the lead, becoming one of the first actors of Asian descent to star in a leading role in American cinema.

Throughout the 1920s and 1930s, Wong appeared in numerous films, showcasing her talent and versatility. Notable films from this period include ""The Thief of Bagdad"" (1924) with Douglas Fairbanks and ""Piccadilly"" (1929), a British film that is often considered one of her most significant roles. Despite her success, Wong was often cast in stereotypical roles and faced discrimination within the industry.","

column1: Tell me a bio of Jean Daullé,Jean Daullé (1703–1763) was a French engraver who gained prominence in the 18th century. Born in Abbeville, France, his early life saw him apprenticed to a jeweler, but his interest and skill in engraving soon became apparent. Daullé's talent led him to Paris, where he studied under the notable engraver Jean-Joseph Balechou. His dedication and skillset saw him being admitted to the Académie Royale de Peinture et de Sculpture in 1736, a significant achievement that marked his acceptance among the elite artists of his time.

Daullé's work is known for its refined technique and ability to capture the nuances of paintings in his engravings. He specialized in portraits, effectively translating the works of various painters into engravings that retained the essence and detail of the original pieces. His skill in capturing the likeness and character of his subjects was highly regarded. Among his notable works are engravings after paintings by Dutch and Flemish masters, as well as portraits of contemporary French figures.

His work helped to establish underwater archaeology as a vital discipline within the broader field of archaeological research.

Tell me a bio of Lewis Nkosi,Lewis Nkosi (1936-2010) was a prominent South African writer, critic, and journalist known for his sharp wit, profound insights into apartheid, and contributions to African literature. Born in Durban, South Africa, into a society deeply divided by racial segregation, Nkosi's early experiences of apartheid's injustices profoundly influenced his writings and his life's work.

Nkosi's career began in the field of journalism, where he quickly gained a reputation for his critical views on apartheid. He worked for the influential Drum magazine, which was a platform for many African writers and intellectuals during the 1950s and 1960s. However, his outspoken criticism of the South African government led to his exile in 1961, a condition that lasted for over three decades.

During his years in exile, Nkosi lived in several countries, including the United Kingdom, the United States, and Zambia. He continued his work as a writer and academic, engaging with issues of race, identity, and the complexities of African diaspora experiences. Nkosi's exile gave him a unique vantage point from which to critique South African society, as well as to explore the broader implications of colonialism and post-colonialism on African identities and literature.

Born on January 25, 1936, in Worcester, Massachusetts, Featherstone was a sculptor by training, having earned a degree in fine arts from the Worcester Art Museum's school.

In 1957, Featherstone joined Union Products, a company in Leominster, Massachusetts, that specialized in plastic lawn ornaments. His assignment to create a realistic flamingo sculpture in 1957 led to the birth of the plastic pink flamingo, officially named the ""Flamingo"" and later affectionately known as the ""Featherstone flamingo."" To create the original sculpture, Featherstone used photos from National Geographic since he had never seen a flamingo in real life. His design was distinctive for its accuracy and attention to detail, and it quickly became a popular lawn accessory in the United States.

column1: Tell me a bio of Takeo Miki,Takeo Miki (1907-1988) was a Japanese politician who served as the Prime Minister of Japan from December 1974 to December 1976. His tenure as Prime Minister was marked by a focus on reform, particularly in response to the Lockheed bribery scandals, which had implicated several Japanese politicians and industrialists. Miki was known for his integrity and his efforts to clean up Japanese politics, earning him the nickname ""Mr. Clean.""

Born in Awa, Tokushima, Miki graduated from Meiji University in Tokyo. Before his prime ministership, he had a long career in Japanese politics. He was first elected to the House of Representatives in 1937. Over his career, he held several key positions, including Minister of Education and Minister of International Trade and Industry. Miki was also a significant figure in Japan's post-war recovery efforts and played a role in the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the dominant political party in Japan during much of the post-war era.

As Prime Minister, Miki sought to implement political reforms to address corruption and restore public trust in the government. His administration faced significant challenges, including economic difficulties and public outcry over the Lockheed scandal. column1: Tell me a bio of Kyu Sakamoto,Kyu Sakamoto, born Hisashi Oshima on December 10, 1941, in Kawasaki, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan, was a beloved Japanese singer and actor. column1: Tell me a bio of Henry Santos,Henry Santos, born Henry Santos Jeter on December 15, 1979, in Moca, Dominican Republic, is a renowned singer, songwriter, and musician, prominently known for his work in the Bachata genre. column1: Tell me a bio of Kim Burrell,Kim Burrell is an American gospel singer, composer, and pastor known for her jazz-inflected vocal style and dynamic performances. Born Kimberly Burrell on August 26, 1972, in Houston, Texas, she has been a prominent figure in the gospel music scene since the early 1990s. Burrell's upbringing in the church, particularly in the Church of God in Christ (COGIC), played a significant role in shaping her musical talents and career.

Kim Burrell's debut album, ""Try Me Again,"" was released in 1995 on the independent label Pearl Records. However, it was her 1998 album ""Everlasting Life,"" released through Tommy Boy Gospel, that gained her significant attention and critical acclaim within the gospel music community. This album showcased her unique vocal style, which blends traditional gospel with jazz and R&B influences, earning her a loyal following.

Throughout her career, Burrell has been celebrated for her vocal virtuosity and innovative approach to gospel music. She has received numerous awards and nominations, including Stellar Awards, which are among the most prestigious awards in gospel music. Burrell has also been a featured artist on recordings with secular and gospel artists alike, including collaborations with Missy Elliott, Frank Ocean","

column1: Tell me a bio of Errol Flynn,Errol Flynn was an iconic Australian-born actor known for his swashbuckling roles in Hollywood films during the 1930s and 1940s. He was born on June 20, 1909, in Hobart, Tasmania, Australia, and passed away on October 14, 1959, in Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.

Flynn's rise to fame began after he moved to Britain as a young man and then to the United States, where he found work in the film industry. He quickly became known for his handsome looks, charismatic presence, and athletic ability, which were perfectly suited to the action-adventure roles that made him a star.

His breakthrough role came in 1935 when he starred as Captain Peter Blood in ""Captain Blood,"" which established him as a leading man. However, it was his portrayal of Robin Hood in the 1938 film ""The Adventures of Robin Hood"" that cemented his place as one of the era's biggest stars. This role showcased his charm and wit, alongside his physical prowess, making the film a timeless classic.
Throughout his career, Flynn appeared in a wide range of films, including ""The Sea Hawk"" (1940), ""They Died with Their Boots On"" (1941","

column1: Tell me a bio of Ramesses IV,Ramesses IV was an ancient Egyptian pharaoh, who reigned during the New Kingdom period, specifically in the Twentieth Dynasty. His reign is generally dated from around 1155 BC to 1149 BC, though exact dates may vary slightly among scholars due to challenges in ancient Egyptian chronology. He was the fifth son of Ramesses III, whom he succeeded on the throne.

Upon his accession, Ramesses IV sought to restore the economic and political stability that had been shaken during his father's reign, partly due to internal turmoil and external threats. He embarked on various construction projects and military campaigns, aiming to reaffirm Egypt's dominance in the region, particularly in areas like Nubia and the Near East.

One of Ramesses IV's notable achievements was his emphasis on mining and quarrying expeditions, especially to the famous turquoise mines of Serabit el-Khadim in the Sinai Peninsula and the stone quarries of Wadi Hammamat. These expeditions were not only for gathering precious stones and materials but also served as a means to demonstrate his power and the extent of his realm.

Ramesses IV also dedicated significant efforts to religious activities, commissioning the construction and expansion of temples, which was a common practice among pharaohs to gain the favor of the gods","

column1: Tell me a bio of Paul Kruger,Stephanus Johannes Paulus ""Paul"" Kruger (10 October 1825 – 14 July 1904) was one of the most prominent figures in the history of South Africa. He was a key leader in the Boer resistance against British rule, serving as the President of the South African Republic (or Transvaal) from 1883 until 1900. His leadership and the struggles during his presidency are closely associated with the period of the Boer Wars, which were pivotal in shaping South African history.

Born in the Cape Colony, Kruger was a fourth-generation Afrikaner of German descent. His family moved northwards as part of the Great Trek, a mass migration of Dutch-speaking settlers (Voortrekkers) who sought to live beyond the British Cape Colony's control. This movement was partly in response to British colonial policies and partly due to the desire for new farming lands. Kruger grew up in the rugged frontier regions of what is today South Africa, developing skills as a hunter and becoming deeply religious.

Kruger first became involved in the politics of the region as a young man, participating in various conflicts and serving in the Volksraad, the parliament of the Transvaal. He was a staunch advocate for the independence","
